Yes — here is a standalone PowerShell script you can run directly on the build server.

It does **not** have an Azure DevOps timeout, so it will keep running until Dependency-Check finishes, fails, or the machine/user stops it. It also matches the way your current templates call the local OWASP CLI, but adds the Java proxy settings that were missing from the pipeline step. Your current template only passes `NVD_API_KEY` and the CLI arguments.  

```powershell
param(
    [string]$ProjectName = "Manual-Dependency-Check",
    [string]$ScanPath = "C:\Repos\MyProject",
    [string]$ReportDir = "C:\temp\dependency-check-report",
    [string]$DataDir = "C:\Tools\dependency-check-data",
    [string]$DependencyCheckCliPath = "C:\Tools\dependency-check\dependency-check-12.2.0\bin\dependency-check.bat",
    [string]$NvdApiKey = "",
    [string]$ProxyHost = "10.0.30.222",
    [int]$ProxyPort = 3128,
    [switch]$UpdateOnly
)

$ErrorActionPreference = "Stop"

Write-Host "========== OWASP Dependency-Check Standalone =========="
Write-Host "ProjectName : $ProjectName"
Write-Host "ScanPath    : $ScanPath"
Write-Host "ReportDir   : $ReportDir"
Write-Host "DataDir     : $DataDir"
Write-Host "CLI Path    : $DependencyCheckCliPath"
Write-Host "UpdateOnly  : $UpdateOnly"
Write-Host "======================================================="

if (-not (Test-Path $DependencyCheckCliPath)) {
    throw "Dependency-Check CLI not found at: $DependencyCheckCliPath"
}

if (-not $UpdateOnly -and -not (Test-Path $ScanPath)) {
    throw "Scan path not found: $ScanPath"
}

New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $ReportDir | Out-Null
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $DataDir | Out-Null

# Make Java use the company proxy
$env:JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS = "-Dhttps.proxyHost=$ProxyHost -Dhttps.proxyPort=$ProxyPort -Dhttp.proxyHost=$ProxyHost -Dhttp.proxyPort=$ProxyPort"

if ([string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($NvdApiKey)) {
    Write-Warning "NvdApiKey is empty. The update may be much slower or rate-limited."
}

$logFile = Join-Path $ReportDir ("dependency-check-" + (Get-Date -Format "yyyyMMdd-HHmmss") + ".log")

Write-Host "JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS = $env:JAVA_TOOL_OPTIONS"
Write-Host "Log file          = $logFile"
Write-Host ""

# Build the argument list
$arguments = @()

if ($UpdateOnly) {
    $arguments += "--updateonly"
} else {
    $arguments += "--project"
    $arguments += $ProjectName
    $arguments += "--scan"
    $arguments += $ScanPath
    $arguments += "--format"
    $arguments += "HTML"
    $arguments += "--format"
    $arguments += "JSON"
    $arguments += "--format"
    $arguments += "JUNIT"
    $arguments += "--out"
    $arguments += $ReportDir
}

$arguments += "--data"
$arguments += $DataDir

if (-not [string]::IsNullOrWhiteSpace($NvdApiKey)) {
    $arguments += "--nvdApiKey"
    $arguments += $NvdApiKey
}

# Keep both Java proxy settings and CLI proxy settings
$arguments += "--proxyserver"
$arguments += $ProxyHost
$arguments += "--proxyport"
$arguments += $ProxyPort

# Same disable flags you are using in your templates
$arguments += "--disableKnownExploited"
$arguments += "--disableHostedSuppressions"
$arguments += "--disableRetireJS"
$arguments += "--disableVersionCheck"

# Add Node-related disables only when doing a full scan
if (-not $UpdateOnly) {
    $arguments += "--disableYarnAudit"
    $arguments += "--disablePnpmAudit"
    $arguments += "--disableNodeAudit"
}

# Optional but useful for troubleshooting
$arguments += "--log"
$arguments += $logFile

Write-Host "Starting Dependency-Check..."
Write-Host ""

$sw = [System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch]::StartNew()

& $DependencyCheckCliPath @arguments

$exitCode = $LASTEXITCODE
$sw.Stop()

Write-Host ""
Write-Host "Dependency-Check finished with exit code: $exitCode"
Write-Host "Elapsed time: $($sw.Elapsed)"
Write-Host "Log file: $logFile"

if ($exitCode -ne 0) {
    throw "Dependency-Check failed with exit code $exitCode"
}
```

Use it like this for a full scan:

```powershell
.\Run-OwaspDependencyCheck.ps1 `
  -ProjectName "Alterna-Telecom-Frontend" `
  -ScanPath "C:\Repos\Alterna-Telecom" `
  -ReportDir "C:\temp\odc-report" `
  -DataDir "C:\Tools\dependency-check-data" `
  -DependencyCheckCliPath "C:\Tools\dependency-check\dependency-check-12.2.0\bin\dependency-check.bat" `
  -NvdApiKey "YOUR_API_KEY" `
  -ProxyHost "10.0.30.222" `
  -ProxyPort 3128
```

And like this if you only want to warm/update the NVD cache:

```powershell
.\Run-OwaspDependencyCheck.ps1 `
  -UpdateOnly `
  -ReportDir "C:\temp\odc-update" `
  -DataDir "C:\Tools\dependency-check-data" `
  -DependencyCheckCliPath "C:\Tools\dependency-check\dependency-check-12.2.0\bin\dependency-check.bat" `
  -NvdApiKey "YOUR_API_KEY" `
  -ProxyHost "10.0.30.222" `
  -ProxyPort 3128
```

My recommendation is:

* run `-UpdateOnly` manually once first
* then run the full scan after the cache is populated

That will usually be much faster than letting the full scan do the first big NVD update itself.

If you want, I can also give you a version that writes everything to a transcript file and retries the whole command automatically if the NVD download fails halfway.
